segments.text: On this episode of Newt's World, Jesse Kelly has written a new book, The Anti-Communist
Manifesto, and he discusses the daily assault Americans are facing on our freedoms from
the insidious Communist movement in this country.
From weaponizing race, sex, and gender, to hijacking our schools, communism threatens
to destroy our cherished American way of life.
The Communist has turned every American institution to a battlefield, from local school boards
to corporate boardrooms and beyond.
Jesse lays out a realistic plan to retake America, institution by institution.
He is one of the most entertaining and fearless conservatives in America.
I'm really pleased to welcome my guest Jesse Kelly.
He is a U.S. Marine veteran, a former Congressional candidate, and host premier networks the Jesse
Kelly show and first TVs.
I'm right with Jesse Kelly.
Jesse welcome and thank you for joining me on Newt's World.
Shoot, it's an honor for me to be here.
It's an honor to sit and get to gab with Newt Gingrich for a little while.
That works for me.
Well, that's great.
Well, you joined the Marine Corps back in the year 2000 and on 9-11 you were watching
the towers fall from inside your barracks and later you deployed to Iraq as an infantry
Marine during the second Persian Gulf War and you received an honorable discharge after
four years.
What was that like to be in the Marines?
And of course, as they say, once you're a Marine, you're always a Marine.
So tell us about the feeling of being a Marine.
I had always grown up with this super admiration of all military service like a lot of young
boys do.
I was always playing with toy guns.
And then when I got old enough, it were real guns and I was always pretending I was John
Wayne out in the woods hunting things.
I would read military books and Marine Corps books.
It was always something I admired.
It was never something I really aspired to do to be quite frank.
And then I graduated high school.
I went to college for one year at Montana State University and I got a 0.0 grade point
average my first semester.
And I obviously had a good time.
But at the end of that year, I thought to myself, I have a lot of growing up I need to
do.
I didn't necessarily like what I was looking at in the mirror.
So I decided, you know what?
I didn't ask my parents.
I didn't talk to anybody.
I walked right down to the Marine Corps recruiting office and walked in and said, I'm signing
up.
I want to be in the infantry.
I was the easiest recruit.
That guy ever got.
And so I joined boot camp all those things.
And then 9-11, I'll never forget that day.
Everyone has a story about where they were that day.
We were out on PT working out as what civilians have called.
We were out working out.
We're doing PT.
And then we got back and we're out in front of our barracks and we're stretching, just
post workout stretching.
A bizarre order came down that we'd never had before.
Get up to your barracks room and turn on the TV.
We'd never heard that before.
We're, what?
Why?
We were upstairs.
And I remember it like it was yesterday.
There was 10 of us probably at least in this one barracks room.
All sweaty, crowded around.
We turned on the television and one of the towers had been hit.
And we were confused because we had been out.
We thought, why are we here watching this?
Why did some idiot accidentally fly a plane into the tower?
We thought it was an accident.
And then we watched live like so many did when the second one came in and then we watched
the towers fall.
And I wasn't the only one with tears coming down my face.
I was ready to go kill people after that.
From there, we ended up in Iraq and the rest is history, I guess you should say.
What are the lessons you took from Iraq?
That our government's garbage, that we have a lot of wonderful people in the Marine Corps
and I was honored to serve with them, that we can't fix problems around the world the
way we've always thought we can.
All forms of government are not made for all kinds of people.
Some people are not simply ready for democracy or republic or whatever we want to call it.
They're not ready and that our government lies.
We're a real big lesson I took from Iraq, not that I'm some anti-war pacifist or anything
like that.
But we were understandably very proud to be there.
We were flying our American flags because this was at the very beginning of the war.
We were in Kuwait and George Bush declared war and then boom, into the country we go
and we're going up through Iraq.
When we were flying our flags, a bunch of very patriotic young Marines and I will never
forget when the order came down from the Bush administration, who knows who it came from,
probably wasn't Bush himself, but the order came down that we were to take down our American
flags and we were not allowed to fly them anymore.
And you've never seen a group of Marines be disheartened that quickly.
We looked around at each other thinking to ourselves, wait, what?
I'm here risking my life, fighting for my country and I'm not allowed to fly the flag
because some Iraqi may be offended by it.
That was the most revealing moment of my life.
That's when I learned a lot about this place.
It strikes me that that was sort of the beginning of the sellout of our core values.
You leave the core.
Do you then go immediately to Arizona?
I do.
I come from a construction family.
Look, I'm poor white trash.
I come from a construction family.
My grandpa did construction in Ohio.
My dad did construction after him in Ohio.
They moved us to Montana.
My folks did when I was 10 and my old man went right back into construction.

That's just what I was going back to do.
So I got out, went right down to Arizona, started going to community college on the GI

I was okay, but a very angry young man.

Radio and things like that.
I started to get political about that time.
As you're doing that, you got very political.

Nobody knew who I was.

This is right before she got shot.
I lost to her by only about 4,000 votes.

So I lost but it was close.

Thank God that didn't work out.
Well, I don't know.
We might have needed your courage and your outspokenness.

What was that like?
I did.
I came back.
I ran in the special.

So he blew my doors off.

So you only signed on to do a one hour show on 950K PRC in Houston.
But then that gets expanded to a two hour show.

on 6 to 9pm Eastern.

He reaches out and he says, hey, you want to come on my show?
Be a guest.

I killed, I guess.

And we ended up getting to be really good friends and he told me this is about five

Well, I kind of scoffed at that.
It piqued my interest.
Long story short, he ends up getting me a one hour at night show on the local station.

So I just kind of fell backwards into all this stuff completely locked out.

Oh, nude.

And I say I don't prepare.
Maybe that's not totally accurate.
